{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532039"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:22:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:22:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14647"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14647"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.4,0.06,0.36,0.11,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7340"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57699"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7340"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14647"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43158"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"45"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1185"},{"type":"tags","id":"1900"},{"type":"tags","id":"2770"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"3564"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11641"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17920"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40296"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43549"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57699","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57699"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 33-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of severe burning pain, swelling, and colour changes in her right hand and forearm. The symptoms developed gradually following a minor wrist sprain. She has a medical history of fibromyalgia and rheumatoid arthritis, which have been stable. Her regular medications include pregabalin, duloxetine, methotrexate, and folic acid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her vital signs are within normal limits. Her right hand and forearm are minimally swollen and feel cold to touch compared to the left side. There is marked hyperalgesia in the affected limb. Active range of motion is limited due to pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal C-reactive protein 4 mg/L (\u0026lt;10), erythrocyte sedimentation rate 12 mm/hr (\u0026lt;20), and normal full blood count. X-ray of the right upper limb shows no bony abnormality.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Physical therapy and rehabilitation","Increase pregabalin dose","Magnetic resonance imaging of right upper limb","Oral corticosteroids","Splinting of the affected hand"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features consistent with complex regional pain syndrome (CRPS) Type I, including disproportionate pain, sensory changes (hyperalgesia), vasomotor changes (temperature differences), and sudomotor changes (swelling). The diagnosis is primarily clinical, and normal inflammatory markers and imaging do not exclude CRPS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhysical therapy and rehabilitation\u003C/strong\u003E is the cornerstone of CRPS management and should be initiated as early as possible. Early intervention with a focus on functional restoration has been shown to improve outcomes and reduce long-term disability. The approach should be gradual and pain-contingent, incorporating graded motor imagery and mirror therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncrease pregabalin dose\u003C/strong\u003E alone would not address the complex nature of CRPS. While medication adjustment may be part of the overall management plan, it should not delay the initiation of physical therapy. Additionally, there is limited evidence for the effectiveness of pregabalin in CRPS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging\u003C/strong\u003E of the right upper limb would not add value at this stage as CRPS is a clinical diagnosis, and the patient already meets the diagnostic criteria based on history and examination findings. Imaging is primarily useful to exclude other conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral corticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E have limited evidence in CRPS and would not be appropriate given the normal inflammatory markers. Furthermore, they may complicate the management of her underlying rheumatoid arthritis and carry significant side effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESplinting of the affected hand\u003C/strong\u003E is generally avoided in CRPS as immobilisation can lead to increased stiffness, muscle wasting, and worsen the condition. Movement and use of the limb, guided by a physical therapist, is essential for recovery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of CRPS requires a multidisciplinary approach, with physical therapy as the foundation. Additional treatments such as psychological support, occupational therapy, and medication adjustments can be incorporated as part of a comprehensive treatment plan. Early recognition and treatment are crucial for better outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Early recognition and treatment of complex regional pain syndrome improves outcomes and reduces disability.","Physical therapy and rehabilitation are the cornerstone of complex regional pain syndrome management.","Normal inflammatory markers and imaging do not exclude complex regional pain syndrome, which remains a clinical diagnosis."],"references":["Taylor SS, Noor N, Urits I, Paladini A, Sadhu MS, Gibb C, Carlson T, Myrcik D, Varrassi G, Viswanath O. Complex regional pain syndrome: a comprehensive review. Pain and therapy. 2021 Dec;10(2):875-92. Available online at ; https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s40122-021-00279-4","Harden RN, McCabe CS, Goebel A, Massey M, Suvar T, Grieve S, Bruehl S. Complex regional pain syndrome: practical diagnostic and treatment guidelines. Pain medicine. 2022 May 1;23(Supplement_1):S1-53. Available online at ; https://academic.oup.com/painmedicine/article/23/Supplement_1/S1/6605306?login=false#359030688"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43158"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14647"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43158","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43158"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-27T13:12:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-27T13:13:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7340"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57699"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"44","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/44"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude79","name":"Pain Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"45","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/45"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83e\uddbd","name":"Rehabilitation Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self"